-- Boeing 737 Family (additional)
('boeing-737-700', 'Boeing 737-700', 'Boeing', 'The smallest member of the 737 Next Generation family, designed to replace the 737-300. Southwest Airlines built its entire fleet around this model, appreciating its reliability and economics for short-haul point-to-point operations.', '1997', '126-149', 6037, 828, 33.6, 34.3, '2x CFM56-7B20', 'Out of Production', 'Southwest Airlines is the largest operator of the 737-700, having standardized its entire fleet on the 737 family for simplified maintenance and crew training.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_737_Next_Generation', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('boeing-737-max-7', 'Boeing 737 MAX 7', 'Boeing', 'The smallest variant of the 737 MAX family, designed to replace the 737-700. Offers 18% lower fuel costs per seat than its predecessor with the same LEAP-1B engines used across the MAX family.', '2018', '138-172', 7130, 839, 35.6, 35.9, '2x CFM LEAP-1B', 'In Production', 'The MAX 7 shares the same wing and landing gear as the larger MAX 8, simplifying production while offering excellent hot-and-high airport performance.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_737_MAX', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

-- Boeing 757 Family (additional)
('boeing-757-300', 'Boeing 757-300', 'Boeing', 'The stretched variant of the 757, and at 54.5 meters the longest single-aisle twinjet ever built. Popular with charter and leisure carriers for high-density holiday routes, offering 20% more capacity than the 757-200.', '1998', '243-295', 6290, 850, 54.5, 38.1, '2x RR RB211-535E4B or PW2043', 'Out of Production', 'Due to its exceptional length, the 757-300 features a retractable tailskid to prevent damage during rotation on takeoff.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_757', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

-- Boeing 767 Family (additional)
('boeing-767-400er', 'Boeing 767-400ER', 'Boeing', 'The largest and final variant of the 767 family with a 6.4-meter stretch over the -300. Features raked wingtips, an updated cockpit, and 777-style interior. Primarily operated by Delta Air Lines for domestic and transatlantic routes.', '1999', '245-375', 10415, 851, 61.4, 51.9, '2x PW4062 or GE CF6-80C2', 'Out of Production', 'The 767-400ER was the first commercial aircraft to use raked wingtips, a technology that would later appear on the 787 Dreamliner.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_767', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

-- Boeing 777 Family (additional)
('boeing-777-200er', 'Boeing 777-200ER', 'Boeing', 'The extended-range variant of the original 777, and the most widely sold version of the entire 777 family. Combines excellent range with the proven reliability of triple-seven operations for long-haul international routes.', '1997', '305-440', 14320, 905, 63.7, 60.9, '2x GE90-85B or PW4084 or RR Trent 884', 'Out of Production', 'The 777-200ER was the backbone of long-haul operations for decades, with over 420 delivered to airlines worldwide before production ended in 2013.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_777', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('boeing-777-8', 'Boeing 777-8', 'Boeing', 'The ultra-long-range variant of the 777X family, designed to replace the 777-200LR. Features the same GE9X engines and folding wingtips as the 777-9 but with a shorter fuselage optimized for maximum range.', '2024', '384-395', 16170, 905, 70.9, 71.8, '2x GE9X', 'In Production', 'The 777-8 can fly farther than any other twin-engine commercial aircraft, capable of connecting virtually any two cities on Earth non-stop.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boeing_777X', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

-- Airbus A320 Family (classic/ceo)
('airbus-a318', 'Airbus A318', 'Airbus', 'The smallest member of the A320 family, nicknamed the Baby Bus. While commercially less successful with only 79 built, it found niche applications including British Airways premium all-business London City to New York service.', '2002', '107-132', 5750, 829, 31.4, 34.1, '2x CFM56-5 or PW6000', 'Out of Production', 'British Airways operated A318s on a unique steep-approach route from London City Airport to New York JFK, requiring special pilot certification.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A318', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('airbus-a319', 'Airbus A319', 'Airbus', 'The shortened variant of the A320, offering the longest range in the single-aisle family. Popular with airlines needing transcontinental range in a smaller package, with over 1,480 delivered worldwide.', '1995', '124-156', 6850, 828, 33.8, 34.1, '2x CFM56-5B or IAE V2500', 'Out of Production', 'The A319 has the best range-to-size ratio in the A320 family, making it ideal for long thin routes that larger aircraft cannot serve profitably.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A319', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('airbus-a320', 'Airbus A320', 'Airbus', 'The original member of the A320 family and the worlds first fly-by-wire airliner in series production. Revolutionized commercial aviation with its digital flight controls and side-stick, becoming the best-selling single-aisle aircraft family.', '1987', '150-180', 6100, 828, 37.6, 34.1, '2x CFM56-5B or IAE V2500', 'Out of Production', 'The A320 pioneered digital fly-by-wire controls in commercial aviation, technology that is now standard across all modern airliners.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A320_family', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('airbus-a321', 'Airbus A321', 'Airbus', 'The stretched variant of the A320 family with a 7-meter longer fuselage. The workhorse for high-density short-haul routes, with American Airlines operating the largest fleet of over 300 aircraft.', '1993', '185-220', 5930, 828, 44.5, 34.1, '2x CFM56-5B or IAE V2530', 'Out of Production', 'The A321 outsold all other A320 family variants combined in later years, as airlines sought more capacity on popular routes.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A321', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

-- Airbus A330 Family (additional)
('airbus-a330-200', 'Airbus A330-200', 'Airbus', 'The shorter-fuselage, longer-range variant of the A330. Offers excellent range for a twin-aisle aircraft, making it popular for long thin routes that cannot support larger aircraft like the 777.', '1997', '210-380', 13450, 880, 59.0, 60.3, '2x GE CF6-80E or PW4000 or RR Trent 700', 'Out of Production', 'The A330-200 can fly routes up to 7,250nm, giving it transcontinental and many transatlantic capabilities in a mid-size widebody package.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A330', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('airbus-a330-800neo', 'Airbus A330-800neo', 'Airbus', 'The shorter variant of the A330neo family with the longest range of any A330. Features new Trent 7000 engines and improved aerodynamics for 25% better fuel efficiency than previous generation aircraft.', '2018', '220-406', 15000, 880, 58.8, 64.0, '2x RR Trent 7000', 'In Production', 'The A330-800neo has the longest range of any A330 variant at 8,100nm, but has attracted fewer orders than its larger -900 sibling.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A330neo', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

-- Airbus A340 Family (additional)
('airbus-a340-300', 'Airbus A340-300', 'Airbus', 'The original and most popular variant of the four-engine A340 family. Developed alongside the twin-engine A330 sharing the same wing, it offered airlines a long-range option before ETOPS regulations expanded twin-engine possibilities.', '1991', '295-440', 13500, 880, 63.7, 60.3, '4x CFM56-5C', 'Out of Production', 'The A340 and A330 were developed simultaneously with the same wing, making them one of aviations most successful parallel development programs.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A340', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20'),

('airbus-a340-500', 'Airbus A340-500', 'Airbus', 'The ultra-long-range variant of the A340, once the worlds longest-range airliner. Designed for extreme long-haul routes like Singapore to New York, it was eventually superseded by more efficient twin-engine aircraft.', '2002', '270-313', 16670, 881, 67.9, 63.4, '4x RR Trent 553', 'Out of Production', 'Singapore Airlines operated the worlds longest non-stop flight with the A340-500 from Singapore to Newark (18+ hours) until the route was suspended due to high fuel costs.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airbus_A340', 'Wikipedia', '2026-01-20');
